She shared pictures of her with her son saying "My one and only beautiful baby boy has transitioned to the heavenly realm. He was only 29. We had a very special love for each other. Rest In Peace my baby. You were my gift from God. Pray for us. #KBug 💔"

Information on cause of death has not been released.

by Mary Gallagher
Office of University Communications
In the grief of immeasurable loss, LaTosha Brown is spending time contemplating the healing power of love – along with its challenges. 

“My heart has to expand,” Brown said Monday in her keynote speech at the MLK Day celebration at Western. “I gotta go deeper in this thing called love.” 

Brown is co-founder of the Black Voters Matter Fund, which is devoted to building and organizing the political power of Black Voters. She had been planning to talk about her work in Georgia focusing on politics and social justice. 

But in a personal, vulnerable speech livestreamed from Georgia to the WWU Performing Arts Center and to viewers online, Brown told the audience she’s been “sitting in all kinds of questions” since her son died unexpectedly a month ago, followed by the deaths of both a dear friend and a beloved uncle in the past week. 

“My pain broke me open. It has broken a place in me that has allowed the light to come in,” Brown said. 

“I am literally sitting in the space where I’m starting to see and believe and feel love can heal all things,” she said. “Love can heal politics of the day. Love can heal and shift and transform our institutions. Love can transform and heal us. We have to be courageous enough to stand in the space to allow ourselves to do that.” 

People too often fail to see the humanity in those who disagree with us and especially in those who would cause us harm, Brown said. But we can’t experience our own full humanity if we avoid the very human experience of pain, she said. 

“If I want people to understand me, I have to create the capacity to understand folks who don’t understand me,” Brown said. “I’ve got to do some work to be able to hold space and hold folks accountable, not to make people feel bad, but to make them rise to a higher occasion, to get to a higher level.” 

The MLK celebration also included a discussion by members of the Whatcom County Racial Equity Commission, a performance of “Poor Man Lazarus” by the WWU Chorale and a land acknowledgement by a student from Northwest Indian College.

“I’m a leader, and the leadership wasn’t afforded to me by the title — it’s by who I am,” Devine said. 
Now, Devine is among the 25 women chosen to be a part of the inaugural class of the Power, Innovation and Leadership executive education program at the Center for Public Leadership at the Harvard Kennedy School. The training program was designed for people who are working to empower Black women and girls in the South and was conceived by LaTosha Brown, who is perhaps most well-known for being the cofounder of Black Voters Matter. A community organizer, political strategist and consultant, Brown has gained a national profile in recent years for the crucial role she played in organizing voter mobilization efforts in Deep South states including Alabama and Georgia. 
Brown deeply believes that “if you change the world for a Black girl, you will literally change the world. When they’re in environments to flourish and thrive, then the whole society will be in an environment to flourish and thrive.” She handpicked the inaugural cohort based upon their demonstrated commitment to their communities, and especially Black women and girls. 
The three-year hybrid program meets once a week and officially began this month. Among the participants are attorneys, formerly incarcerated women, reproductive justice advocates, social venture capitalists and those who are directly working to enact policy change. Brown was intentional about including women from diverse sectors because one of the main goals of the program is for Black women in the South to have expanded access not only to institutional knowledge, but to peers. It aims to allow the women to think more critically about power, innovation and leadership via scholars and one another.

The Southern Black Girls and Women’s Consortium is all about making Black Girl Dreams come true… even if that means sending a young girl to Phoenix, Arizona to dance during the 2023 Super Bowl half-time show with @badgalriri!⁠
⁠
⁠
It all started in August 2022 during the kick-off of the Southern Black Girls’ inaugural Joy is Our Journey Dream Bus Tour in Atlanta. The event was filled with a host of activities including interactive workshops and programming centered around mental health and wellness, beauty, arts and culture, entrepreneurship, S.T.E.M. and dream-building. Amidst the experience, @Jemiahalex , who was performing that day as one of the Joy is Our Journey dancers, made an on-camera declaration of her “Biggest Dream.” Her dream was to, one day, dance in the #SuperBowl, and thanks to the Southern Black Girls, that dream came true!⁠
⁠
We immediately reached out to @RocNation and Megan @theestallion @PeteThomasfdn , who partnered with us on the #JoyisOurJourney Dream Bus Tour, to see if there was a possibility to make Jemiah’s dream come true!⁠
⁠
In January 2023, Jemiah received a surprise phone call from Megan the Stallion congratulating her on the opportunity. Watch the story unfold on Southern Black Girls YouTube Channel, click the link in bio NOW!⁠

Meghan to receive Ms. Foundation's Women of Vision Award

Meghan, the Duchess of Sussex, and Black Voters Matter co-founder LaTosha Brown will receive the Ms. Foundation’s Women of Vision Award in May, the nation’s oldest women’s foundation announced Monday

By GLENN GAMBOA - AP Business Writer 16 hrs ago
Article link: https://www.thesunchronicle.com/business/meghan-to-receive-ms-foundations-women-of-vision-award/article_fbd07a2f-e669-54dc-b860-c0bd9a49d5a2.html

In 2018, I was invited to Harvard for an IOP fellowship and I never left. I have been at this institution in some capacity every since. I remember thinking about how transformative the fellowship was for me. 

I was so inspired that I decided that one day I would create a special program for Black women working in the south at Harvard. I would create a program that would both honor them and push them to move to the next level of their leadership. 

A few years later I started putting my vision in motion. I started having conversations with a renowned Harvard professor, DrJulie Batallia at SICI . And soon after I brought on my colleague and friend, Chancee Lundy, to help me create/co-design an accredited program with Harvard faculty that would support the leadership advancement of women working for Black girls and women in the south. 

I so believed in this vision that I underwrote the entire program with money I set aside for my retirement ( with the exception of a generous $50K grant from the Libra Foundation) I had hoped that foundations and companies that touted a commitment to investing in Black women would come thru. But in all honesty most of the calls I had only led to non-committal discussions. While I was disappointed I stayed determined to see this work to fruition. 

I wanted this experience to be at no cost to the women participants. I wanted them to know that they are worthy of investment and perpetual support for leadership advancement, growth and development. I wanted them to feel valued, appreciated and poured into. I wanted them to be seen. 

With God’s help we launched the first accredited Power, Innovation and Leadership Executive Education cohort at Harvard the top of the year. We kicked it off only two weeks after I buried my only child. But as God would have it, the launch of my program was therapeutic and healing to me. It was a light in a dark moment in my life. 

Over the past four months, I’ve watched these inspiring 25 women form new relationships, shift perspectives, push back of traditional leadership models and blossom through their own Black brilliance and boldness.
Let Patience have her perfect work in you ❤️🎓
Faculty of the. power, Innovation and Leadership Executive Education program at Harvard.

The power of Eight (8). 🌺Eight (8) Black southern women have been working together for the past five years to create a network of Black women and girls, expand opportunities for Black girls and raise and deploy millions in resources for girls in the south. I’m so proud of our work. It’s amazing to watch this vision unfold in such beautiful and extraordinary ways. We are the Southern Black Girls & Women’s Consortium. 

We are still reeling from the 3rd Annual Southern Black Girls & Women’s Consortium’s Black Girls Dream conference held last week in Memphis. We have grown the conference from 300 attendees to 600 to now more than 1300+ Black girls and women and we are still growing. 

In less than 5 years, we have built a robust network of hundreds of grassroots orgs that serve and/or led by Black girls, we have granted millions of dollars to groups to build organizational capacity, we have directly funded 550 girls to develop community JOY projects, we have provided organizational development trainings, workshops, philanthropy training and direct support to community members working with Black girls and much more. 

We are creating a new model for philanthropy that is rooted in a self determination model. Every  single aspect of our work is led, envisioned, developed and implemented by Black women and girls of the south. 

This work has been implemented and led by a small and mighty staff that includes four dynamic leaders aka The Joy Team that includes (Chancee Lundy, Joy Webb, Jelecia Clinton and Malikah Rogers-Berry (Executive Director) and the work has been anchored by Felecia Lucky, Margo Miller, Alice Easton Jenkins and myself. 

We are very very proud of what we have been able to accomplish so far and we are just gettting started. I’m excited to be on this journey with these amazing Black women as we work to generate more opportunities, build a 100+ million dollar fund, distribute resources for our network, help our network strengthen and expand and generate unlimited amounts of JOY with Black girls and women in the south. Learn more about our work at www.southernblackgirls.

🧘🏾‍♂️Last year, this time I was bathing in mud in the Totumo Mud Volcano in Colombia. I was on a trip with 25 Black girls through the youth group founded by my friend Chancee Lundy called Destination Liberation, 

The mud volcano is located near a coastal Carribean city of Cartagena. This is the first time ever that I took a mud bath inside an actual volcano. It was suppose to have healing properties for the skin. 👧🏽

It’s interesting that the buoyancy of the mud causes you to float and prevents you from sinking although it’s about 30 feet deep.

The Lawyers’ Committee hosts the Higginbotham Awards gala annually to highlight the exemplary contributions of corporate executives, policy makers, professional athletes, authors, artists and other individuals who champion the cause of justice and equality for all.

The Higginbotham Leadership Awards Gala
is named in honor of A. Leon Higginbotham, Jr. a celebrated statesman, civil rights champion, author, professor, historian, and federal appeals court judge.

The Lawyers’ Committee hosts the Higginbotham Awards gala annually to highlight the exemplary contributions of corporate executives, policy makers, professional athletes, authors, artists and other individuals who champion the cause of justice and equality for all. The gala is one of the largest events in the civil rights community. This year’s gala will be held on October 4th in Cipriani Wall Street, NY. 

We invite you to join us as we build partnerships that foster a culture of democracy and amplifies voice, opportunity and power of  Black people and other communities of color.

I’ve increased my workout days and my trainer has increased the intensity of my workouts. I’m going to maximize the health and wellness of this body God gave me to steward. 

Nine months ago the grief, physical exhaustion and lack of sleep had me so arrested that I was having trouble with basic movements like walking and standing for long periods. I had low energy, felt constantly tired and barely wanted to walk to my mailbox. Well baby I’m BAAACCCKKK!! 

I’ve taken charge of my life and making better choices for me. 
I am still navigating through the grief of the loss my only child and battling insomnia but the physical movement, fun activities and lifestyle changes are making a huge difference in how I feel. 

My workout videos are not pretty nor are they intended to show me as some fitness guru or workout example. I am only sharing my journey to hopeful inspire someone who has allowed themselves to become sedentary over the years and not maximize the beautiful machine of a body that God has given you. 

I am intentionally healing myself, generating joy in my life, incorporating health and wellness as a core value in my life, attracting the love i desire, enjoying friendships that bring me joy, brining new opportunities in my life, creating the life I deserve, navigating through my pain and getting FINE as wine within the next year. 

I hope that in my sharing that someone that may be navigating or experiencing grief as I am, will be inspired to GET UP, GET FIT, DO your emotional, physical and mental work, GENERATE MUCH JOY and GO GET YOUR LIFE BACK! ❤️

I’m transforming. Since my son’s death I’ve been committed to not allow the grief and sadness take over my life. The first few months I felt like I was watching my life outside of my body. I felt disconnected from myself. I was just suspended in time. 

Instead of fighting the feelings I embraced and surrendered to them. I decided to see the suspension of myself as floating on God’s grace and mercy through my grief. 

I then decided to recommit to bring  myself back into my body. I soon realized just how physically and emotionally abusive I have been to myself over the years. Instead of my health been a top concern it was literally dead last. 

So I gathered myself, got my mind right and started off with a Yoga teacher coming to my home so I could practice  in private (while oftentimes crying during the movements) just to get me back into my own body. 

Three months later I decided that in the famous words of Beyoncé, I needed to “go harder.” So I started grief therapy and hired a personal trainer to help me push my body to new levels of fitness through circuit training. 

💗I’m so proud of me. I can now see a measure of progress. No surgeries, no pills, or no extreme diets. I’ve just been working out 2-3 times per week. 

I’ve been losing weight and gaining muscle after 3 months of working out with my personal trainer Yasmin Bano. I’ve still got a ways to go but I’m halfway there. 

By next summer I will be rocking a 2peice bikini! Imma be NAKED! LOL 😂 Watch me work!

Today my heart is heavy. A few days ago I found out that my father died as we were traveling back from Disney World. We didn’t have the traditional daughter daddy relationship and it was never constant contact but neither was it contentious. We rarely talked but when we did it was always interesting conversations. His absence in my life growing up impacted me greatly and in ways that I’m still discovering. 

He was a gifted musician. I grew up hearing that he was an amazing saxophone player. I always felt my gift of music was from him and I always imagined that perhaps one day we would record a song together. 

From a child I believed that the music would be our love language and bring us together as a family. I felt like we could co-write at least one song that would repair the broken pieces of both of our hearts. I think I shared the idea of doing music together and he was kinda sorta open to it. 

I pray that Abram Brown is resting in God’s perfect peace. Even though I don’t remember him ever saying it to me — I know he loved me. He lived his life on his on terms and in his own way.  I forgave him and loved him. I hope that he knew it. Rest in peace Daddy.❤️
